text: I was disappointed to hear that the story behind one of the greatest documentaries ever made "Man on Wire" has now been made into a film. The thing that made Man on Wire so great was the charisma and storytelling abilities of it's subject, Philippe Petit. That and the breathtaking photo stills of the "actual" high wire act and film score/editing. I can't see The Walk improving upon or advancing this amazing story....only taking away from it with a bloated CGI account of an historic event. It seems Hollywood is desperate to make yet another feel good piece about the Twin Towers at the expense of the remarkable talent: Philippe Petit.

I mentioned to two coworkers that I was amazed that this letter would go across country and then up so high. I was not only made fun of but ridiculed. They laughed at me. These buildings were not admired by most people at that time. Nobody back then would even think of making a movie like this. One of the coworkers, who was a russian immigrant, said he was up there and that it was no big deal even. I left the place in 1999, so I'm not sure if they remembered the conversation.

text: When I saw the first few seconds of this trailer, I thought it was going to be yet, another movie about 9/11 and I'm glad to see it isn't. I think that they made this movie to show that there are other interesting stories about the Twin Towers than just about the day they were destroyed. Other guys have done crazy things on the Twin Towers, too. One guy named Owen J. Quinn actually jumped off the roof of the North Tower with a parachute in 1975. Another guy named Dan Goodwin climbed the North Tower using suction cups in 1983, in 1981 he climbed the Sears Tower in Chicago the same way wearing a Spider-Man costume. To this day, he still climbs high buildings.

text: As a solipsist I want you all to know that I created this movie with my mind. For a long time I have been studying the 'hell' out of 9/11 from both the truth movement perspective to the official story and it makes absolutely no sense. It defies logic. Thus like Renes Descartes I am convinced that the collective or more aptly the singular reality is just a figment of a godlike imagination. So what I would like to share with you is a little clue to how these directors like Robert Zemeckis are more wizards than men. By thy fruits ye shall know them. Ever heard that expression? Robert created two movies that tie into one another. "Back to the Future" and "Contact". Without getting into too many revealing details he was using these movies as vehicles to share a symbolic message with either a receptive collective conscience or a select group of individuals who would be able to decipher this cryptic message. This suggests in and of itself that there are those amongst us who follow a cryptic code. One might assume they are extra-terrestial beings but that would not be the case because they have their feet on the ground just like everyone else. In fact the extra-terrestial idea is really nothing more than a symbol for what we as humans already are aware of, that there is a spirit world. I am going on the hunch that one third of the host of heaven as mentioned in the bible exists here amongst us. They don't communicate with each other consciously thus you will not catch them in some conspiratorial verbal agreement. And they are not visually identifiable, so they would cross over all racial profiles. I have personally met some of these fallen angels. And a clue to how you recognize them is how when they drift out of your day to day environment, they seem to pop up 'randomly' in places that defy coincidence. So in all likelihood this person may be a family member, a former boyfriend or girlfriend, a colleague at work. I once even tried to test one of them by avoiding them after I spotted them from a distance because my eyesight and facial recognition ability is really quite keen. After hiding in different places to avoid them I found them trailing behind me purposely seeking me out and pretending when they did catch up to me that it was a surprise encounter. They would say "Hey, fancy meeting you here".

text: For me it's not the question of balls, lots of people have them. What stunned me is sky high level of confidence, an absolute dead calmness that he had that day and that he was able to do his routine not 20 meters above the ground but 400 m. Petit didn't just walk the wire he also did kneeling and laying down. It's also amazing how he was able to conquer weather conditions, I thought wind would have been bigger problem that high up. While watching a movie I remembered several times of 9/11 jumpers. The views Petit had that day in August 1974 was the same as they had 27 years later in most unfortunate circumstances. I'm not afraid of heights (I go to mountains often), but during that Walk scene I felt like butterflies in my stomach are going absolutely insane. Probably best stunt performance of all times.

text: Upon watching these trailers I've come to realise what a poignant movie this is. I know it really happened when I was a teenager but to watch it expresses two things: what Philippe did was an incredible feat which paid homage to the twin towers but what the terrorists did was incomprehensible, not just to the buildings but to the hardworking Americans on that tragic day. I loved this movie as it brought the towers back to life with special wonderful affects & we got to see them again in all their true glory in 3D too if you were lucky enough to see it thanks to Philippe's amazing stunt but also  sad to realise they are now gone because of a cruel act that the world will never forget.

text: I watched this on AXN channel with my parents who were both in their 80s.  I got so very worried because both my Dad and Mom couldn't get a hold of their nerves during that wire-walk.  They stood up and started inch-walking away from the TV saying Oh my God-‚ÄïOh my God‚ÄîOh my God. Oh my God‚Äï Oh my God.  They just kept repeating OMG !  that I got so worried for my Mom that I rushed up and turned the TV off but right away they told me to turn it back on.  So there we were all three of us standing there and watching the guy wire-walking between the Twin Towers.  By then my parents were almost huddled together at the corner of the living room saying OMG OMG OMG OMG !   I was so so worried for my parents then. They were in good spirits after. But I seriously thought the three of us died a little that night.  In my case from the worry...
